SQL General Query Commands

Show databases

	SHOW DATABASES


Show all tables 

	SHOW TABLES


Show columns from a certain table

	SHOW COLUMNS FROM table_name


View a table

	SELECT * FROM table_name


Update a value in a table 

	UPDATE tablename
	SET Column1 = value1,
   		 Column2 = value2,
  		  …
    		Columnn = valuen
	WHERE criteria

	*Update using a function

	UPDATE table_name
	SET ColumnName = REPLACE(ColumnName, 'string_search_term', 'replacing_term')


Insert a row in a table

	INSERT INTO tablename
      			(column1, column2, … columnn)
      			VALUES (value1, value2, … valuen)
Note: Text values are encapsulated in single quotes


Delete from a table

	DELETE FROM tablename
	WHERE criteria e.g. ID = 1
Note: If where clause ommited, all data from table will be deleted


Create a table

	CREATE TABLE table_name (
   		ID int NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT,
		LastName varchar(255) NOT NULL,
    		FirstName varchar(255),
		Age int,
 		PRIMARY KEY (ID))


Add column to table

	ALTER TABLE table_name ADD dateOfBirth date


Rename column name

	ALTER TABLE table_name
	CHANGE column_name new_name varchar(100)


Delete table

	DROP TABLE table_name



Get info from multiple tables

	SELECT table_name.column_name, table_name2.column_name FROM table_name, 				table_name2



Order output from SQL Command

	SELECT * FROM table_name
	ORDER BY e.g. LastName, Age


Collating data from two tables using JOIN

	SELECT table_name.ColumnName, table_name.ColumnName, table_name2.ColumnName, 		table_name2.ColumnName 
	FROM table_name JOIN table_name2 ON table_name.Column1 = table_name2.Column1
	WHERE table_name.ColumnName = ('String')
	GROUP BY table_name.ColumnName


Query when joining two tables where something is equal from THIRD table

	SELECT Sales.SaleNo, Sales.SaleDate, SaleProducts.Quantity, SaleProducts.ProductID
	FROM Sales JOIN SaleProducts ON Sales.SaleNo = SaleProducts.SaleNo
	WHERE SaleProducts.ProductID IN (SELECT ProductID
									FROM Products
									WHERE BrandID = 1)




SQL Mathematic Functions

ABS()
The ABS() function returns the absolute (positive) value of the specified numeric expression. The
below SQL statement will return 1.0, 0.0 and 1.0.

	SELECT ABS(-1.0), ABS(0.0), ABS(1.0)


CEILING()
The CEILING() function returns the smallest integer greater than, or equal to, the specified
numeric expression. The below SQL statement will return 124, -123 and 0.

	SELECT CEILING(123.45), CEILING(-123.45), CEILING(0.0)


FLOOR()
The FLOOR() function returns the largest integer less than or equal to the specified numeric
expression. The below SQL statement will return 123, -124 and 0.

	SELECT FLOOR(123.45), FLOOR(-123.45), FLOOR(0.0)


ROUND()
The ROUND(numeric_expression , length [ ,function ] ) function returns a numeric value, rounded
to the specified length or precision. A function of zero rounds the number, whilst a function of 1
truncates the number. The below SQL statement will return 123.9990 and 124.0000.

	SELECT ROUND(123.9994, 3), ROUND(123.9995, 3)

The below SQL statement will return 151.00 and 150.00.

	SELECT ROUND(150.75, 0), ROUND(150.75, 0, 1)


POWER()
The POWER (float_expression , y ) function returns the value of the specified expression to the
specified power. The below SQL statement will return 8.

	SELECT POWER(2, 3)

There are many other mathematical functions such as COS(), SIN(), TAN(), LOG(), PI(), RADIANS(),
SIGN(), SQRT(), SQUARE() and others.



SQL Date Functions

GETDATE()
The GETDATE() function returns the current date and time. The below SQL statement will return
something like: 2016-06-08 10:43:48.827.

	SELECT GETDATE()


YEAR(), MONTH() and DAY()
The YEAR(date), MONTH(date) and DAY(date) functions return the year, month and date of a
supplied date. The below SQL statement will return something like 2016, 6 and 8.

	SELECT YEAR(GETDATE()), MONTH(GETDATE()), DAY(GETDATE())


DATEPART()
The DATEPART(datepart, date) function returns an integer representing a datepart of a date. The
following two SQL statements will return something like 2016.

	SELECT DATEPART("Year", GETDATE())

	SELECT DATEPART("yy", GETDATE())

Note: that the date part is encapsulated in double quotes.


