DATEADD()
The DATEADD(datepart, number, date) function returns a new date/time value after adding a
number that represents a date or time interval to the specified datepart. The number parameter
must evaluate to an integer, and the date parameter must evaluate to a valid date. The below
SQL statement adds one month to the date 08 Jun 2016 and will return 2016-07-08
00:00:00.000:

	SELECT DATEADD("Month", 1, '08 JUN 2016')

The below SQL statement adds five days to the date 08 Jun 2016 and will return 2016-06-13
00:00:00.000:

	SELECT DATEADD("Day", 5, '08 JUN 2016')


DATEDIFF()
The DATEDIFF(datepart, startdate, endate) function returns the number of date and time
boundaries crossed between two specified dates. The datepart parameter identifies which date
and time boundaries are to be compared. The below SQL statement will return 60.

	SELECT DATEDIFF("dd", '01 Feb 2016', '01 APR 2016')

The DATEDIFF() function is a great function to calculate how long it has been since you lent your
mate Bob 50 dollars which he has still not paid back.

SQL String Functions

LEN()
The LEN() function returns length of string. The below SQL statement will return 10.

	SELECT LEN('John Smith')


LOWER()
The LOWER() function converts all characters to lowercase characters. The below SQL statement
will return john smith.

	SELECT LOWER('JOHN SMITH')


UPPER()
The UPPER() function converts all characters to uppercase characters. The below SQL statement 
will return JOHN SMITH.

	SELECT UPPER('john smith')


LTRIM()
The LTRIM() function removes all spaces on the left of a given character string. The below SQL
statement will return 'John Smith'.
	
	SELECT LTRIM(' John Smith')


RTRIM()
The RTRIM() function removes all spaces on the right of a given character string. The below SQL
statement will return 'John Smith'.

	SELECT RTRIM('John Smith  ')


LTRIM() and RTRIM()
Both the LTRIM() and RTRIM() functions do not remove tab or line feed characters. To remove all
spaces from both the left and right of a given character string, use both of the LTRIM() and
RTRIM() functions.

	SELECT LTRIM(RTRIM('  John Smith  '))


SUBSTRING()
The SUBSTRING(character_expression, position, length) function returns a part of string from an
original string. Position specifies where the substring begins and length specifies the length of
the substring in terms of the number of characters. The below SQL statement will return 'Smit'.

	SELECT SUBSTRING('John Smith', 6, 4)


REPLACE()
The REPLACE(character_expression, searchstring, replacementstring) function replaces a sub
string within the original string. Searchstring is the string which you want to replace.
Replacementstring is the new string which you want to replace it with. The below SQL statement
will return John Jones.

	SELECT REPLACE('John Smith', 'Smith', 'Jones')

All instances of the seachstring will be replaced. The below SQL statement will return John Jones
Jane Jones.

	SELECT REPLACE('John Smith Jane Smith', 'Smith', 'Jones')


LEFT()
The LEFT(character_expression, length) function extracts a number of characters from the left
side of a given string expression. The below SQL statement will return ‘John’.

	SELECT LEFT('John Smith', 4)

RIGHT()
The RIGHT(character_expression, length) function extracts a number of characters from the right
side of a given string expression. The below SQL statement will return ‘mith’.

	SELECT RIGHT('John Smith', 4)


CHARINDEX()
The CHARINDEX (search_expression, character_expression, [, start_location ]) function returns
the starting position, if found, of the search expression within the character expression. You can
optionally specify a start location. The below SQL statement will return 6.

	SELECT CHARINDEX('Smi', 'John Smith')

The below SQL statement will return 12.

	SELECT CHARINDEX('Smi', 'John Smith Smith', 7)








